Mean Absolute Error (MAE) - Practice Problem
We’re testing how well our prediction model works.
To do this, we compare the actual values (true outcomes) with the predicted values (model’s output).

The Mean Absolute Error (MAE) tells us, on average, how far our predictions are from the actual results.

Smaller MAE = better predictions
Larger MAE = less accurate model
Example Dataset

Actual (y_true)	Predicted (y_pred)
30	28
45	50
50	47
65	60
80	85
Task

Use mean_absolute_error from scikit-learn.
Pass y_true and y_pred to it.
Print the MAE value.
Expected Output

MAE: 4.0

#########  HERE IS THE CODE  ########

from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error

# Actual vs Predicted values
y_true = [30, 45, 50, 65, 80]
y_pred = [28, 50, 47, 60, 85]

# Calculate MAE
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true , y_pred)
print("MAE:", mae)

